( { When the idea of publishing a simplified repertoire was presented to me, I saw it as an interesting challenge. The goal was to present a complete repertoire against }1.d4 { , }1.c4 { , and }1.Nf3 { without cutting out any critical theory.  We have taken great measures in selecting lines for trainable variations that have occurred most frequently in the database and our test games. We have also added many clickable variations for rare sidelines and untested lines of interest. When there is a honeycomb of overlap in variations, we placed clickable sidelines to not overtrain similar variations.  As always in a Tillis text, if you have a reasonable question, comment on the move of the most similar variation in the text, and he will get back to you!    As a note, the Priority Lines have been set to the most significant and important theoretical variations and it is a good place to start your study after reading through the introduction. } )1. d4
1. Nf6{ In lieu of a Quickstarter Guide, in this course we will do an overview of the most critical variations in the first few informational lines. }
2. c4{ This will easily be the most frequently occurring move you will face. }
2. c5
3. d5
3. g6{ We will be angling for the Late Benoni in this course. It should be noted that my choice to go for this move order stems mostly from personal preference to avoid long theoretical forcing variations. I find lines like the following in the Modern Benoni quite difficult and this is the main line. }( 3...e6 4.Nc3 exd5 5.cxd5 d6 6.e4 g6 7.f4 { By far the most popular move in the database against the Modern Benoni. }7...Bg7 8.Bb5+ Nfd7 9.a4 O-O 10.Nf3 Na6 { Best, with the idea to go to  b4  and then  a6  to get the strong  b5 -bishop out. }11.O-O Nb4 12.Re1 a6 13.Bf1 Re8 { So far this has been a series of only moves for Black but the engine still teeters at close to +1. }14.h3 f5 { Another only move; otherwise, Black will not find counterplay. }15.Bd2 fxe4 16.Nxe4 Nf6 17.Nxf6+ Bxf6 18.Qb3 { With 50 games in the database, Black has won only three here.     Overall, these lines are playable in over-the-board chess but the chances to go from one point in the hole to losing is a thin line and it requires the player to be both very strong and creative to find best play consistently. With our move order we completely avoid this line by White along with many other dangerous systems simplifying our repertoire! } )
4. Nc3
4. Bg7
5. e4( 5.Nf3 { We will use this move order to get to the ever-popular Fianchetto Variation. }5...O-O 6.g3 e6 7.Bg2 exd5 8.cxd5 d6 { As a player who has played the King's Indian Defense, Grünfeld, Benko Gambit, and Benoni, I have found that these lines are underrated and seen far less frequently than the big two in fianchetto player's games. We can definitely look forward to the surprise value element. }9.O-O { Now, we won't go for the popular secondary move }9...a6 { . We do not know if we will need that move in the Benoni, and it is often just automatically met by }10.a4 { , so it is better to hold off on that move.  Instead, }{   }9...Re8 { leaves us with far more flexibility. }10.Nd2 { The mainline, looking for the knight to jump to  c4  to pressure  d6 . }10...b6 { This cuts down on the large amount of theory generated from }10...a6 { . It is a more solid move that directly plays against White's natural plan.  The Fianchetto Variation is covered in  Chapter 13.  } )
5. d6{ Only now do we play ... d6  to stop the progress of the White  e -pawn. }
6. Nf3( {  A)  }6.Bd3 { This flexible move will likely be a transposition, but we have touched on independent tries. }6...O-O { The move order difference between ... e6  and ... O-O  is negligible in this variation. The reader should take note of the lines where ... e6  first matters, as we will be using rare move orders in an attempt to get White out of their book and into ours! }7.Nge2 e6 8.O-O exd5 9.cxd5 { Easily the most popular capture. }9...a6 10.a4 Nbd7 11.h3 Ne5 { Putting the question to the bishop and attempting to provoke White into  f4 . As well will see in  the trainable variations,  this very easily can become overextension. } )( {  B)  }6.Be2 e6 7.Bg5 { This falls under the  Averbakh  Variation of the King's Indian Defense. }7...exd5 8.exd5 { The better of the two captures, which have been tested almost equally. }8...h6 9.Be3 Bf5 { We get into novel territory with this move. It has only been played once by Suetin in 1972. We really like this move as it provokes White to play the natural  g4  which will result in a double-edged position. } )( {  C)  }6.h3 { This is a useful move for White in multiple variations and has the highest possibility of transposition. }6...e6 7.Bd3 { We label  these variations  falling under the King's Indian Defense, Makogonov Variation. }7...exd5 8.cxd5 O-O { will transpose to the main variation in this Introduction after }9.Nf3 { . } )( {  D)  }6.f4 { King's Indian Defense,  Four Pawns Attack.  It is a point of interest that after }6...O-O 7.Nf3 e6 8.Be2 exd5 9.cxd5 Nbd7 { , with over 350 sample games in the database, Black is scoring better than White with this relatively modern move which keeps the tension. }10.O-O Re8 { This places immediate pressure on the center. }11.Nd2 c4 { We would happily trade a wing pawn to break the strong center. From the standpoint of White playing this variation to be aggressive, it sure does seem like we have already taken that away in the mainline. }12.Kh1 b5 13.Nxb5 { The only move that has been played in practice. }13...Nxe4 { We have broken the center with a great game! } )( {  E)  }6.f3 { King's Indian Defense,  Saemisch Variation.  Our move order will be }6...O-O { and the best thing about it is that it avoids all of the lines where White could oversimplify, as the center is already locked. We are guaranteed to have a fighting game! }7.Bg5 e6 8.Qd2 exd5 9.cxd5 a6 { Throughout the repertoire, anytime we play ... a6  White will seek to stop us with the natural  a4 . }10.a4 { Needless to say, if White does not play this move, we are happy to grab space with ... b5 . }10...h6 { A useful tactical move. }( { (The  h6 -pawn is poison: }11.Bxh6 Nxe4 { followed by ... Qh4 + picking up the strong attacking bishop. }{ ) } )11.Be3 Re8 12.Nge2 Nbd7 { In practice, Black has a better score with this move than White, coming in at 53% in our favor. } )( {  F)  }6.Nge2 { This is the Bagirov or  Serper Variation  of the King's Indian Defense. }6...e6 7.Ng3 h5 { White wants to play on the kingside, and we clearly have a say in this matter. }8.Be2 Nh7 { A novelty in a rare position. This should keep the specialist on their toes as the natural play with  Bg5  is no longer available. } )( {  G)  }6.Bg5 { Last in frequency but certainly not least. }6...e6 { Playing this before castling potentially avoids a large chunk of theory where White plays for caveman tactics with  Qd2 ,  h4 , etc. }7.Bd3 h6 { A formal request to pick up the bishop pair. }8.Bh4 exd5 9.cxd5 { This move was played here in the database in nine out of ten cases }9...O-O 10.Nge2 { The most flexible move, showing the benefit of waiting on the development of this knight. }10...Nbd7 11.O-O Ne5 { Black has been doing well here in practice. See more  here.  } )
6. O-O
7. h3( 7.Be2 { This is the mainline with the most frequency in the database, but in our practice, we found  h3  at this juncture to be more popular at higher levels to avoid the  Bg4  ideas. }7...e6 8.O-O exd5 9.cxd5 Bg4 { Our star move; very often in the Benoni, this bishop looks for something to do. In this variation, we part with the bishop to have more control over the critical  e5 -square. }10.Bf4 { The best practical move by White to eye the Benoni-pawn. }10...a6 11.a4 Bxf3 12.Bxf3 Qe7 13.Re1 Nbd7 { We have full control over the critical square. }14.Qc2 h5 { This is a critical move, and Memory Marker starting our plan on the kingside. We will be able to play ... Nh7  and have the flexibility to move the dark-squared bishop to  e5  or  d4  with good play. See more  here.  } )
7. e6
8. Bd3
8. exd5( { With branches in both }9.exd5 { and }9.cxd5 { . } )
9. cxd5{ This goes down the path of the traditional Modern Benoni. Though this is a close second in the database, we faced it far more often in our practice games. }( 9.exd5 { This is arguably the most dangerous variation in the entire opening complex. The reader needs to have this as a high priority. }9...Re8+ 10.Be3 { We provide two options here: the interesting and speculative }10...Rxe3!? { as an  alternative  and the popular }10...Bh6 11.O-O Bxe3 12.fxe3 Qe7 { Do not be in a hurry to capture the  e -pawn, it will lead to doom. }13.e4 Nbd7 { Much like many of our variations, control over  e5  is critical. }14.Rf2 Rf8 { A necessary prophylactic move to cover the  f -pawn for the future. }15.Qd2 Ne5 16.Nxe5 Qxe5 17.Qf4 Ne8 { A novelty in the position encouraging White to create a passed  d -pawn which will quickly be blockaded. See more  here.  } )
9. b5{ A necessary move to strike before White can consolidate the position. }
10. Nxb5{ The better capture for White. }( 10.Bxb5 Nxe4 { We need to keep the pressure on, while the king is stuck in the center. }11.Nxe4 Qa5+ 12.Nfd2 Qxb5 { We have grabbed the bishop pair but will be forced to give it back. }13.Nxd6 Qa6 { The best square for the queen. }14.N2c4 Nd7 15.O-O Ne5 { The best square for the knight, centralized and attempting to break the link between  c4  and  d6 . }16.Nxc8 Raxc8 17.Nxe5 Bxe5 { Practice has shown that this is the best path to equalize and play for a win. See more  here.  } )
10. Re8{ This is far better than any other move. }
11. O-O
11. Nxe4
12. Re1
12. a6
13. Na3{ White wants the  c4 -outpost. }
13. Nf6{ We were required to retreat, but it comes with an important idea. }
14. Rxe8+
14. Nxe8{ The  d6 -pawn is well defended. }
15. Bg5
15. Bf6{ There are multiple options for Black here but this is the best scoring currently in the database. Our study continues  here.  }
