1. Nf6{ In lieu of a Quickstarter Guide, in this course we will do an overview of the most critical variations in the first few informational lines. }
2. Bf4{ The London System, if White plays  Nf3  at some point. }( {  A)  }2.Nc3 d5 3.Bf4 { The Jobava-London. }3...g6 4.e3 Bg7 5.h4 { This is easily the most popular move. White wants easy expansion and aggression... Our answer is no. }5...h5 6.Nf3 { Continuing the theme of the most popular move in the database. }6...O-O 7.Ne5 { White eyes the kingside structure. We need to get the ball rolling on the attack. This is not a position where we can wait for White to attack us. }7...c5 { An important structural move and Memory Marker to pressure White as quickly as possible. }8.Qd2 Nc6 9.O-O-O Qa5 { The queen is well placed on the queenside eyeing the pin and the  a2 -pawn. }10.Kb1 cxd4 { Only one game has been played so far with this move, but it seems best. }11.exd4 Bf5 { Time and again in these lines, this is seen as the strongest square for the bishop, even in the face of  f3  and  g4  by White. }12.Nxc6 bxc6 13.f3 Rfb8 { Yes, we are willing to part with the exchange to attack, and the machine is a believer. The line continues  here.  } )( {  B)  }2.Nc3 d5 3.Bg5 { The Veresov. }3...g6 { Whenever possible, we will stick to our fianchetto theme. }4.Qd2 h6 { We are unafraid to lose a tempo in order to gain the bishop pair and dynamic chances. }5.Bf4 Bg7 6.O-O-O c6 { This is a key move signaling the attack on the queenside. Do not get this confused with the Jobava-London lines, which look very similar. So, what is the difference? We have not castled; therefore, there is no clear and easy attack for White on the kingside! We, on the other hand, can start action immediately due to the  c6  pawn lever. }7.f3 b5 { With dynamic attacking chances as seen  here.  } )( {  C)  }2.Bg5 g6 3.Bxf6 exf6 4.e3 d5 { This is an important move to define the structure. It is important to note that we will never have an isolated pawn playing against the Trompowsky. That would lead to a dream position for White. }5.c4 { Arguably the best attempt White has in the position. As the lines have a distinct structural orientation, we will leave the majority in clickable format. }5...dxc4 { This is a key move and Memory Marker. We can't allow a structure with an isolated  d -pawn. }6.Bxc4 Bd6 { The most popular move in practice and stays with a developmental theme throughout the Trompowsky lines. }7.Nc3 f5 8.Nf3 Nd7 9.O-O O-O 10.Rc1 c6 { Stopping the action on the  c -file with a solid structure. See more  here.  } )( {  D)  }2.e3 g6 3.Nf3 Bg7 4.Bd3 { The first move which indicates that White seeks to play the pure Colle System. }4...c5 { Any pressure we can quickly apply against a systematic player is suggested. It gives them pause and more room to deviate from their precious system. }5.O-O O-O 6.c3 { It is now clear that White will be playing the mainline with the tempo-losing  e4  push. }6...d6 { We will be using the same structure as with the London System. We, in fact, encourage White to waste time by touching their  e -pawn for the second time in the opening. }7.Nbd2 Nc6 8.Qe2 { The most popular move by a decent margin. }8...e5 { A key move and Memory Marker in the position. We need to play ... e5  to ensure that White will never have the opportunity to play the move himself. This is a critical idea in the structure, as allowing White to play  e5  will disrupt our piece harmony and give White a space advantage. }9.dxe5 dxe5 10.e4 Nh5 { We seek at the right moment the use of this strong square. The line continues  here.  } )( {  E)  }2.f4 { Stonewall Attack. }2...g6 3.e3 Bg7 4.Nf3 O-O 5.Bd3 c5 { Easily the most testing move order. We would like for White to break the wall for us by capturing, which will create an easy target. }6.c3 d6 { The best antidote to facing the Stonewall is to break it! This is a strong theme that I use in the English Opening against the Stonewall Dutch. }7.O-O Nc6 8.Nbd2 e5 { The key move and Memory Marker to break that wall! The line continues  here.  } )
2. g6{ We will stick to the most aggressive move order with fianchetto-based systems. }
3. e3
3. Bg7
