1. Nf6{ In lieu of a Quickstarter Guide, in this course we will do an overview of the most critical variations in the first few informational lines. }
2. g3( {  A)  }2.e3 g6 3.d4 Bg7 4.Be2 { Easily the more passive square for the bishop. White has no issue with accepting no opening advantage and angles for a colors reversed Tarrasch Queen's Gambit Declined. }4...c5 { An early capture on  c5  will be handled via transposition in  this  clickable variation. }5.O-O O-O 6.c4 { The most natural of the options. }6...cxd4 7.exd4 d5 { We have now reached the not-so-theoretical colors reversed Tarrasch. }8.Nc3 dxc4 { A good moment to capture as we will tempo the bishop. }9.Bxc4 Bg4 { Best, as it creates some pressure on the isolated pawn with natural play. More on this  here.  } )( {  B)  }2.b3 { Delayed Nimzo-Larsen. This is covered in the  Queen's Pawn Oddities  chapter. }2...g6 { It will be important to develop our bishop to  g7  to stop any ideas of White capturing on  f6  doubling our pawns. }3.Bb2 Bg7 { It is important to cover the knight. We don't want to end up in a bad version of a Trompowsky. }4.e3 { These lines have a high chance of transposing into other covered variations. }4...O-O 5.Be2 c5 6.O-O Nc6 7.c4 { This line could very well be located in our English Chapter as well. }7...d5 { The best way to deal with the hedgehog setup. }8.cxd5 Qxd5 { The best capture as we would like to maintain tension to play for a win. Don't make unnecessary trades! }9.d3 Rd8 10.a3 { Is best here to cover the  b4 -square from invasion. }10...b6 11.Nbd2 Bb7 { No need to go to  a6  to encourage White to develop to  c4  to stunt the attack. }12.Qc2 e5 { This is best as we claim space with an improved Maroczy Bind structure from the Sicilian colors reversed, of course. Our coverage of the Delayed Nimzo-Larsen continues  here.  } )( {  C)  }2.b4 { Santasiere's Folly. }2...e5 { Arguably the most direct approach to facing this very rare sideline. }3.Nxe5 Bxb4 4.Bb2 O-O 5.g3 d5 6.Bg2 Nbd7 { This is a bit more forcing deviating from 0-1  (65) Nakamura,H (2768)-Aronian,L (2735) Chess. com INT 2022. }7.Nf3 Nb6 { We look to utilize the space left behind that the  b -pawn would have occupied. This is the key move and Memory Marker of the variation, which continues  here.  } )
