1. c4( 1.d4 { With our Benoni lines, we can often reach the English via different move orders. }1...Nf6 2.Nf3 { This is a solid move order very often used by players looking to avoid many sidelines in modern  1.d4  theory. }2...g6 { This allows for the most aggressive responses against the sidelines. We will not have symmetry! }3.c4 c5 4.Nc3 { White opts to avoid the Benoni and attempts to maintain tension. }4...cxd4 { Much like the Sicilian Defense, when we have the opportunity to capture on  d4 , it is typically the best move. We have now transposed back into the English. }5.Nxd4 d5 { We will not give White the time to set up the optimal Maroczy Bind structure. }6.cxd5 { Easily the most popular move in the database. }6...Nxd5 7.Ndb5 { We need to be mindful of potential tactics here. }7...Nxc3 { An only move, don't forget it! }8.Qxd8+ Kxd8 9.Nxc3 Bg7 { Black has been performing well from this simplified position. See more  here.  } )
1. Nf6{ In lieu of a Quickstarter Guide in this course we will do an overview of the most critical variations in the first few informational lines. }
2. Nf3( {  A)  }2.Nc3 c5 { This will be our move order for the  2.Nc3  English. }3.g3 d5 { We need to play ... d5  now! It is essential before White gets the bishop on  g2  to shut down this idea. }4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.Bg2 { Putting the question to the knight. There are many transpositions and move orders to get back to covered variations. We'll show them  here  in clickables. }5...Nc7 { We need to lose a bit of time here to reach colors reversed Sicilian waters with the best chances to outplay the opponent. }6.Nf3 Nc6 { We control the  d4 -square and get ready to secure the center. }7.O-O e5 { We have reached a colors reversed Maroczy Bind structure. }8.d3 { Easily the most popular move in practice, but it is of note how to handle some of the sidelines, which are included  here  as clickables. }8...Be7 9.Nd2 Bd7 10.Nc4 f6 { A solid Maroczy Bind Reversed which has been scoring well for Black in practice. See more  here.  } )( {  B)  }2.Nc3 c5 3.e4 { White will reach a Botvinnik structure from this move order. }3...Nc6 4.g3 g6 { We will head to an optimal Dragon-style pawn structure. }5.Bg2 Bg7 6.Nge2 O-O 7.O-O d6 8.d3 a6 { This is the first move indicating our plan in the position. A key move and Memory Marker - we plan to break on  b5 ! }9.h3 { An important move to secure the  e3 -square for the bishop. We very well have ... Ng4  in mind if White shirks this move. }9...Rb8 10.a4 { White has more influence over the  b5 -square. Let's change that. }10...Ne8 11.Be3 b5 { The fourth choice move in the database but favored highly by the machine. More on this  here.  } )
2. c5{ The symmetrical English. Let's see how quickly we break symmetry to play for a win. }
3. Nc3
3. g6
4. g3( 4.e4 Nc6 5.d4 cxd4 { An essential move. We can't allow White to gain further space with the  d -pawn. With this capture, we have transposed into a Maroczy Bind Sicilian in the Accelerated Dragon. }6.Nxd4 Nxd4 { Unlike the mainline Maroczy Accelerated Dragon trading off one set of knights helps us avoid the deep theoretical battle and improves Black's chances. GM Guseinov has often played this with good results. }7.Qxd4 d6 { Covering the key squares so White has no immediate move to increase tension. }8.Be2 Bg7 9.Be3 O-O 10.Qd2 { We have reached the main tabiya for these variations. }10...a5 { When looking at all the options, this move in connection with the following was the best scoring and most interesting approach at restraining White. }11.O-O a4 { We have, in the least, stopped rapid expansion plans where White flings the entire queenside at us. }12.f3 { The most common move in practice. We will include a few other variations stemming from this line as clickables to show standard play. This will provide the reader with ideas on how to handle the bind position. }12...Qa5 { Reaching a setup that is played quite frequently in our repertoire. See more  here.  } )
4. d5{ We will not allow White time to get the bishop on  g2  with potential discovered tactics in the center. It is the time to strike in the English Symmetrical Mainline! }
5. cxd5
5. Nxd5
6. Bg2
6. Nc6
7. d3{ Easily the top choice, but we will leave  a few  rare sidelines to show the reader how to handle the obscure positions. }
7. Bg7
