4. O-O{ We first complete development on the kingside before making any firm commitment to strike the center. This allows us flexibility to choose the most testing plan for our opponent. }
5. Be2( 5.h3 { Makes no significant difference in our plan. }5...c5 { With a very likely transposition into the mainline. } )( 5.c3 { A bit of a rare move order which will likely transpose into our mainline. }5...d6 6.Bc4 { This is an independent try that is rare but worth mentioning, as it popped up in our practice games when testing the course. }6...c5 7.O-O Qb6 8.Qb3 Nh5 { A novelty that is best in an attempt to wrestle the bishop pair from White. This deviates and improves on 0-1 (43) Bachran,B (1975)-Giemsa,S (2322) Berlin 2015. }9.Bg5 Nc6 { Covering the  e7 -pawn. We have no worries of }10.d5 { as our  e7 -pawn is covered tactically. }10.Bh4 h6 11.Nbd2 g5 { A theme that will pop up in many sidelines throughout the course. }12.Bg3 Na5 { Black has solid pressure and the better part of equality. } )( 5.Bd3 { This move misplaces the piece as it encourages Black to perform the King s Indian slam of  e5  in the center with the eventual threat to fork the  f3 -knight and  d3 -bishop. In the very least White will lose time in this variation which is why it is not popular for White. }5...c5 { We kick things off with the same structure from our main trainable variation. }6.c3 d6 { If at any time White captures the c-pawn he has made the decision to abandon the center and we have easy equality and a tempo on the bishop. }7.Nbd2 Nc6 8.O-O cxd4 { We soften up the center before playing the natural  e5  slam. In the database this has been played in less than fifteen games with  exd4  happening in nearly all cases. It should be noted that we play  e5  with a great game in either case. }9.exd4 e5 { The pawn is tactically defended due to the ill-placed  d3 -bishop. }10.Bg3 exd4 11.Nxd4 Nxd4 12.cxd4 Nh5 { went well for Black following 0-1 }{ (30) }{ Planas Ferret,R }{ (2275) }{ -Munoz Pantoja,M }{ (2375) }{ Barcelona 2002. } )
5. c5
6. c3( { Giving up the center gives Black a very easy game. }6.dxc5 Qa5+ 7.c3 Qxc5 { The author has always felt strongly about this type of position. We get easy development and flexible plans. White gives up the center for easy development and pitches the first-move advantage. }8.Nbd2 d5 { This claims control over the key break squares. }9.Nb3 { In practice, this has been by far the most popular move to date. }9...Qb6 10.Qd4 Nbd7 { improves on ½-½ (35) Szmetan,R  (2305) -Gruchacz,R (2335) Illinois 1986. Black will look to play in the center as the game continues. Another idea to look for, if White captures on  b6 , is to relocate the knight to  a4 . } )( 6.O-O { changes nothing with our plan. }6...d6 { With a very likely transposition to the main line. } )( 6.Nc3 d5 { gets back to themes  seen  in our Jobava-London lines. } )
6. d6
7. dxc5{ One of the few attempts to alter the structure. The machine gives this rough equality but the position feels easier for Black to play. }
7. dxc5
