3. Bg5
3. g6{ Whenever possible, we will stick to our fianchetto theme. }
4. Qd2( 4.Bxf6 exf6 { transposes into our  Trompowsky  structure. } )
4. h6{ We are unafraid to lose a tempo in order to gain the bishop pair and dynamic chances. }
5. Bf4{ Easily the most natural and thematic move. }( {  A)  }5.Bxf6 { The reader should be comfortable with this structure after going through the variations on the  Trompowsky.  After }5...exf6 6.e3 c6 7.g3 h5 { , though we have used an extra tempo, we still have excellent chances with a position with the same themes as the Trompowsky mainline. } )( {  B)  }5.Bh4 { With less than ten games in the database, this will remain a clickable footnote. }5...Bg7 6.f3 c6 { The standard theme in our Veresov lines. }7.e4 dxe4 8.fxe4 e5 { Equalized for Black following: 0-1 (34) Neff,S (2310)-Sepp,O (2425) Tallinn 1997. }9.Nf3 exd4 10.e5 { This continuation needs to be noted due to its forcing nature. With the queens off the board, there will be no attack and no issues. }10...dxc3 11.Qxd8+ Kxd8 12.exf6 Re8+ 13.Be2 Bh8 { Temporary undevelopment; the  f6 -pawn will eventually fall. }14.O-O-O+ Nd7 { The attack is done; we will slowly uncoil with equal chances. } )
