2. c5( { The optimal move order against  2.c4  for our repertoire. It should be noted that }2...g6 { can be played, but we feel there are more options to go wrong for the first player with the Benoni/Benko move order, as seen in the sidelines. } )
3. dxc5{ A refuge for the uninitiated! Why release the tension? Fear would be the typical answer to that question. }( 3.e3 { We will often see this move from many different move orders, but we will land by transposition into one of two structures seen within the course. }3...g6 4.d5 { would get back into more passive Benoni lines for White. The main move is }4.Nc3 Bg7 5.Nf3 { Typically, if White did not play  d5  earlier, they will not change their mind now, and we will reach the end of the clickable variation. Now }5...O-O 6.Be2 cxd4 7.exd4 d5 { gets back to our Colors Reversed Tarrasch, covered  here  with our Colle lines. } )
3. e6{ The best and most straightforward idea to combat the doubled pawns. }( 3...g6 { is a completely feasible alternative for those who enjoy fianchetto structures. It should be noted that the engine favors }3...e6 { by a wide margin. } )
4. Nc3( 4.Be3 { The only move to make a serious attempt at holding on to the doubled pawn. }4...Qa5+ 5.Nd2 Bxc5 6.Bxc5 Qxc5 { Black will have no issues completing development. } )
4. Bxc5
5. Nf3{ There will be many different move orders here, but the general plan will come down to two different pawn structures. The first will be with an isolated pawn, and the second with a symmetrical pawn structure. }
5. O-O
6. e3( 6.e4 { This space gaining move is terrible! }6...Ng4 { Black already has a big edge. } )
6. Nc6
7. Be2
7. d5{ We need to strike in the center as that gains space and will potentially help complete development. Our  c8 -bishop would like to join in the fight. }
8. cxd5{ We are far more likely to face the colors reversed Queen's Gambit Accepted position. }( 8.O-O dxc4 { If White has given us the opportunity to tempo the bishop and gain time, we should take it. }9.Bxc4 a6 { A strong multi-purpose move. It also allows White to trade queens, which would be a mistake as we would get the open  d -file for the rook. }10.a3 b5 11.Be2 Bb7 12.b4 Bd6 { Black had some slight pull and went on to win following 0-1 (39) Pesout,J  (2251)-Vacek,M (2308) Czech Republic 2008. } )
8. exd5
9. O-O( 9.a3 a6 { A good move allowing our bishop to drop back to  a7  in the event of  b4 . We need flexibility with this bishop for our coming kingside attack. } )
9. Re8
10. b3( 10.Na4 Bd6 { We will not allow our good bishop to come off the board. } )
10. Bg4
11. Bb2
11. a6{ We again see this strong multi-purpose move. We are now fully developed and ready to begin the assault. }
12. Rc1
12. Ba7{ Black begins the typical plan. }
13. h3
13. Bf5( { This is best, as }13...Bh5 { can be met by }14.Nh4 { equalizing, as seen in ½-½ (47) Narayanan, S (2529)-Gelfand, B (2684) Moscow 2019. } )
14. Bd3( 14.Na4 Rc8 { We deviate here from ½-½ (30) Willems,N (2338) -Riff,J (2444) Switzerland 2022. }15.Nc5 Qe7 16.Bxf6 { This capture will add spice to the position. We have the bishop pair for the price of doubled pawns and the potential of using the open  g -file in the future to attack. }16...gxf6 17.Nh4 Bg6 { We would have no issue with White capturing and fixing the pawn structure. }18.Nd3 d4 { Black finds the right moment to use the isolated pawn with a dynamically balanced position. } )
14. Ne4{ Positive tension is the name of the game. }
15. a3{ To stop the idea of ... Nb4 . }
15. Qd7{ A flexible move. We have the follow-up of ... Rad8 . }
16. Ne2{ This is the type of move we need to watch out for. Black has two reasonable options here. }
16. Rad8{ With a balanced game where Black is optically the aggressor. }( 16...Nxf2 { This sacrifice may very well throw a player off their game. }17.Rxf2 Bxe3 18.Rc2 Bxd3 { Black is in no hurry to alleviate the tension on the  f2 -rook. }19.Qxd3 Qd6 { The machine gives both lines a roughly balanced evaluation. It comes down to the player's taste. } )
